Detailed Description

A dummy object that resides in the header node for a tree.

Using a header node can simplify insertion logic by eliminating the need to check whether the root is null. The actual root of the tree is generally stored as the right child of the header node. In order to always proceed to the actual root node when traversing down the tree, instances of this class always return NSOrderedAscending when called as the receiver of the -compare: method.

Since all header objects behave the same way, all search tree instances can share the same dummy header object. The singleton instance can be obtained via the +object method. The singleton is created once and persists for the duration of the program. Any calls to -retain, -release, or -autorelease will raise an exception. (Note: If garbage collection is enabled, any such calls are likely to be ignored or "optimized out" by the compiler before the object can respond anyway.)

Member Function Documentation

- (NSComparisonResult) compare: (id)  otherObject

Always indicate that another given object should appear to the right side.

Parameters:
otherObjectThe object to be compared to the receiver.
Returns:
NSOrderedAscending, indicating that traversal should go to the right child of the containing tree node.
Warning:
The header object must be the receiver of the message (e.g. [headerObject compare:anObject]) in order to work correctly. Calling [anObject compare:headerObject] instead will almost certainly result in a crash.
